[[File:Frances Evelyn Boscawen ne<U+00E9> Glanville.jpg|thumb|Frances Evelyn Boscawen n<U+00E9>e Glanville (23 Jul 1719 <U+2013> 26 Feb 1805)]]
'''Frances Evelyn Boscawen''' (n<U+00E9>e '''Glanville''') (23 July 1719<U+2013>26 February 1805) was known as a literary hostess, correspondent and member of the [[Blue Stockings Society|Bluestockings Society]].<ref name="ODNBweb">{{ODNBweb|id=47078|title=Boscawen , Frances Evelyn (1719<U+2013>1805)|first=Elizabeth|last=Eger}}</ref>

Frances Evelyn Glanville was born on 23 July 1719 at St Clere in Kent.  In 1742 she married [[Edward Boscawen]] (1711<U+2013>1761).  When Edward's work in the navy took him away from home Frances sent him passages from her journal, some of which were later published.<ref name="ODNBweb" /><ref name=AdmiralsWife>{{cite book|last=Aspinall-Oglander|first=Cecil Faber|title=Admiral's wife; being the life and letters of the Hon. Mrs. Edward Boscawen from 1719 to 1761.|year=1940|publisher=Longmans, Green and co|location=London|coauthors=Frances E. G. Boscawen}}</ref><ref name=AdmiralsWidow>{{cite book|last=Aspinall-Oglander|first=Cecil Faber|title=Admiral's Widow: Being the Life and Letters of the Hon. Mrs. Edward Boscawen from 1761 to 1805|year=1943|publisher=Hogarth Press|location=London|coauthors=Frances E. G. Boscawen}}</ref> 
==Family==
Their children were:

*Edward Hugh, born 13 Sept 1744, died 1774
*Frances, born 7 March 1746, died July 1801
*Elizabeth, future wife of the [[Henry Somerset, 5th Duke of Beaufort|duke of Beaufort]], born 28 May 1747
*William Glanville Boscawen, born 11 August 1749, died 21 April 1769
*[[George Boscawen, 3rd Viscount Falmouth|George]], born 6 May 1758, succeeded his uncle as third [[Viscount Falmouth]]. 


After Boscawen's death in 1761, Frances returned to her London house at 14 South Audley Street, where she became an important hostess of [[Blue Stockings Society|Bluestocking]] meetings. Her guests included [[Elizabeth Montagu]], [[Samuel Johnson|Dr Johnson]], [[James Boswell]], [[Joshua Reynolds]], [[Frances Reynolds]], [[Elizabeth Carter]], and later [[Hannah More]], who described her as 'sage' in her 1782 poem ''The Bas Bleu, or, Conversation'', published in 1784.<ref>{{cite book|last=More|first=Hannah|title=Florio, a tale for fine gentlemen and fine ladies ; and, The bas bleu, or, Conversation two poems.|year=1786|publisher=T. Cadell|location=London|page=86|url=http://www.archive.org/stream/florioataleandb00moregoog}}</ref>  Her widowhood inspired [[Edward Young]]'s 1761 poem ''Resignation''.<ref name="ODNBweb" />  She "was widely known in literary London as a model letter writer and conversationalist, prized for her wit, elegance, and warm heart," according to a present-day scholar.<ref name="ODNBweb" /><ref>[http://www.katelynludwig.com/masters/bluestocking_members/member_biographies/frances_boscawen.html ''Frances Boscawen'' Reinventing the Feminine: Bluestocking Women Writers in 18th Century London]</ref>

Frances died at home in London 26 February, 1805.<ref name="ODNBweb" />
